><td>4:00 pm</td><td>to</td><td>5:00 pm</td></tr></table><p>On Friday, March 13 at 4:00pm, Kim McLean-Fiander will be leading a public &ldquo;Nuts and Bolts of DH&rdquo; discussion on digital remediation processes remedying past archival practices that have concealed women from history.&nbsp; The details are below.</p>\n<p>Finding Women in the Archives: Digital Remedying &amp; Remediation</p>\n<p>Kim McLean-Fiander</p>\n<p>Abstract</p>\n<p>Through a case study of Women&rsquo;s Early Modern Letters Online (WEMLO), Kim McLean-Fiander calls attention to how, in the process of re-mediation, digital projects must not miss the opportunity also to remedy the deficiencies of past archival practices that have effectively hidden women from history. The traditional definition of &ldquo;remediation&rdquo; is the &ldquo;act or process of remedying something that is undesirable or deficient.&rdquo; For media critics, &ldquo;re-mediation&rdquo; is the &ldquo;incorporation or representation of one medium in another medium&rdquo; (Bolter and Grusin). This discussion will explore the challenges and possibilities emerging from the re-mediation, in both senses of the word, of a print finding aid into a digital one.</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://etcl.uvic.ca/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/TheAveragePenguin.png\"><img src=\"http://etcl.uvic.ca/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/TheAveragePenguin.png\" alt=\"TheAveragePenguin\" width=\"359\" height=\"242\"></a></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>by caitlinelizabethmullen</p>\n<p>https://theaveragepenguin.wordpress.com/2012/10/30/remediation/</p>\n<p>Bio</p>\n<p>Kim McLean-Fiander is Co-investigator (with Professor James Daybell at The University of Plymouth) of Women&rsquo;s Early Modern Letters Online (WEMLO), a British Academy-funded project that will produce a freely available digital finding aid and editorial interface for women&rsquo;s correspondence from the early modern period. WEMLO was conceived during her previous post as Editor of Early Modern Letters Online (EMLO), the union catalogue of sixteenth-, seventeenth-, and eighteenth century correspondence produced by the Cultures of Knowledge project at the University of Oxford. Kim completed her doctorate at Oxford on early modern women&rsquo;s paratext. She was also an&nbsp; intern with the Curator of Manuscripts at the Folger Shakespeare Library, a Senior Library Assistant at the Bodleian Libraries, and a freelance editor for a number of years. She is currently a lecturer in English at the University of Victoria and Associate Director and Managing Editor of The Map of Early Modern London (MoEML).</p>\n<p>Time and Location</p>\n<p>Friday, 13 March 2015<br>\nUniversity Club<br>\nUniversity of Victoria<br>\n4:00-5:00pm</p>\n<p>Sponsored by the The Electronic Textual Cultures Laboratory at the University of Victoria (http://etcl.uvic.ca/) and organized by Matthew Hiebert, this is the third of four entries in the Nuts and Bolts of Digital Humanities discussion series for this academic year.</p>\";s:7:\"myimage\";N;s:8:\"myAuthor\";s:5:\"admin\";s:12:\"itemcategory\";s:6:\"Events\";s:7:\"mycatid\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"myGroup\";s:34:\"ETCL at the University of Victoria\";s:6:\"feedID\";i:421;s:13:\"useMediaImage\";i:0;}}'),(2844,7406,'rssmi_item_date','1425058976'),(2845,7406,'rssmi_item_feed_id','421'),(2852,7412,'rssmi_item_permalink','http://etcl.uvic.ca/2015/02/27/brown-bag-lisa-goddard-on-library-services-for-digital-humanists/'),(2853,7412,'rssmi_item_description','a:1:{i:0;a:11:{s:9:\"mystrdate\";i:1425074972;s:7:\"mytitle\";s:71:\"Brown Bag: Lisa Goddard on “Library Services for Digital Humanists”\";s:6:\"mylink\";s:96:\"http://etcl.uvic.ca/2015/02/27/brown-bag-lisa-goddard-on-library-services-for-digital-humanists/\";s:6:\"mydesc\";s:3246:\"<table><tr><td colspan=\"3\">March 12, 2015</td></tr><tr><td>12:00 pm</td><td>to</td><td>1:00 pm</td></tr></table><p>The Electronic Textual Cultures Laboratory at the University of Victoria<br>\n(<a href=\"http://etcl.uvic.ca/\">http://etcl.uvic.ca/</a>) invites you to attend the fourth meeting of the<br>\n2014-5 <strong>Brown Bag Speaker Series</strong>. This is a series of informal lunchtime<br>\nseminars for faculty and graduate students in the Faculty of Humanities<br>\nand across the university to discuss issues in digital literacy, digital<br>\nhumanities, and the changing face of research, scholarship, and teaching<br>\nin our increasingly digital world. For an hour once per month, we meet<br>\nto hear from an invited speaker, share ideas, and build knowledge.</p>\n<p>On <strong>Thursday March 12th</strong>, from 12 until 1 p.m., <strong>Lisa Goddard</strong> (Associate University Librarian for Digital Scholarship and Strategy) will be presenting a talk entitled,</p>\n<p><strong>Library Services for Digital Humanists.</strong></p>\n<p>Details are below. Please share this announcement with anyone who might be interested in attending.</p>\n<p>Tuesday March 12th,12 &ndash; 1 p.m.<br><strong>David Strong Building, Room C128</strong>, University of Victoria</p>\n<p>Abstract: New modes of knowledge production in the Digital Humanities emphasize collaboration, scale, and interdisciplinarity. Emerging digital research environments are able to ingest large amounts of text and image data, to support the contribution of annotations and revisions by multiple researchers, to enrich texts with geographic, bibliographic, and numeric data, and to allow for semantic tagging and linking. Humanist researchers are a core constituency for libraries and archives, and the University of Victoria Libraries are challenged to transform traditional collections and services to better align with the demands of digital scholarship.</p>\n<p>UVic Libraries are developing a new suite of services for digital scholars. These include digitization services, open licensing, digital publishing, content hosting, and digital preservation. We intend to develop and articulate these services so that they can easily be included in grant applications and project proposals. Libraries will continue to be an indispensable part of the research continuum as the humanities undergo their digital transformation. Come to this session to help us shape UVic library services to best meet your needs.</p>\n<p>Bio: Lisa Goddard is the Associate University Librarian for Digital Scholarship and Strategy at University of Victoria Libraries. She holds degrees from Queen&rsquo;s, McGill, and Memorial University, and is currently completing an MA in Humanities Computing at the University of Alberta. Lisa&rsquo;s research interests include open access publishing, semantic web technologies, digital publishing &amp; preservation, and digital humanities.</p>\n<p>Bring your lunch and join us to discuss digital technologies and research in our community!</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://etcl.uvic.ca/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/posterGoddard.png\"><img src=\"http://etcl.uvic.ca/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/posterGoddard-791x1024.png\" alt=\"posterGoddard\" width=\"791\" height=\"1024\"></a></p>\";s:7:\"myimage\";N;s:8:\"myAuthor\";s:5:\"admin\";s:12:\"itemcategory\";s:6:\"Events\";s:7:\"mycatid\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"myGroup\";s:34:\"ETCL at the University of Victoria\";s:6:\"feedID\";i:421;s:13:\"useMediaImage\";i:0;}}'),(2854,7412,'rssmi_item_date','1425074972'),(2855,7412,'rssmi_item_feed_id','421'),(2856,7415,'_edit_lock','1425084663:3'),(2857,7415,'_edit_last','3'),(2858,7415,'incsub_wiki_email_notification','0'),(2871,7425,'rssmi_item_permalink','http://etcl.uvic.ca/2015/02/28/etcl-talk-at-ideafest-and-open-house/'),(2872,7425,'rssmi_item_description','a:1:{i:0;a:11:{s:9:\"mystrdate\";i:1425083142;s:7:\"mytitle\";s:36:\"ETCL talk at Ideafest and Open House\";s:6:\"mylink\";s:68:\"http://etcl.uvic.ca/2015/02/28/etcl-talk-at-ideafest-and-open-house/\";s:6:\"mydesc\";s:1522:\"<table><tr><td colspan=\"3\">March 4, 2015</td></tr><tr><td>2:30 pm</td><td>to</td><td>5:30 pm</td></tr></table><p>Hello all,</p>\n<p>We hope that your semester is going well! Things are buzzing along over here at the Electronic Textual Cultures Lab, and we would like to take this opportunity to formally invite you to a springtime Open House at the ETCL. Are you curious about digital humanities initiatives at UVic? Wondering what sort of projects are going on in the ETCL at the moment? We&rsquo;ll have many of our ETCL members on hand to share their ideas and initiatives with you, as well as to engage in discussion and answer any questions you may have.</p>\n<p>When: Wednesday March 4th, 4.15pm-5.30pm<br>\nWhere: Electronic Textual Cultures Lab (ETCL), Clearihue B043b (between HCMC and the CALL centre)<br>\nWho: ETCL members, including staff, post-docs, programmers, and graduate and undergraduate research assistants<br>\nSnacks: Provided</p>\n<p>A couple of representatives from the ETCL will also be presenting at IdeaFest earlier that day, during the panel &ldquo;Humanities in a Lab Coat: Another Kind of Research Life&rdquo; (2.30pm-4pm, ECS 108), and we would love to see you there as well. Please see attached flyer for more info.</p>\n<p>All best,<br>\nAlyssa, on behalf of the ETCL team</p>\n<p>&mdash;<br>\nAlyssa Arbuckle (B.A. Hons, M.A.)<br>\nAssistant Director, Research Partnerships &amp; Development<br>\nElectronic Textual Cultures Lab | University of Victoria<br>\nalyssaarbuckle.com | @arbuckle_alyssa</p>\";s:7:\"myimage\";N;s:8:\"myAuthor\";s:5:\"admin\";s:12:\"itemcategory\";s:6:\"Events\";s:7:\"mycatid\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"myGroup\";s:34:\"ETCL at the University of Victoria\";s:6:\"feedID\";i:421;s:13:\"useMediaImage\";i:0;}}'),(2873,7425,'rssmi_item_date','1425083142'),(2874,7425,'rssmi_item_feed_id','421'),(2875,7426,'_edit_lock','1432336810:3'),(2876,7426,'_edit_last','3'),(2877,7426,'cs_page_builder','<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<pagebuilder><page_content>Yes</page_content><page_sub_title/><header_banner/><page_title>Yes</page_title><sidebar_