10:20','[woocommerce_thankyou]','Order Received','','publish','closed','open','','order-received','','','2014-01-08 13:10:20','2014-01-08 13:10:20','',6780,'http://chimpgroup.com/wp-demo/aidreform/checkout/order-received/',0,'page','',0),(6821,3,'2014-01-08 14:12:43','2014-01-08 14:12:43','<h3>Frequently Asked Questions</h3>\r\nSeveral of the questions refer to Wiki Help Docs, which can be found <a href=\"http://www.itercom.org/wiki/\" target=\"_blank\">HERE</a>\r\n\r\n[accordion]\r\n[accordion_item active=\"yes\" title=\"What is Iter Community?\" accordion=\"accordion\"]Iter Community is a social knowledge creation environment facilitating and supporting communication, collaboration, and digital project creation for research communities of the Middle Ages and the Renaissance. See our <a href=\"http://www.itercom.org/about-us/\" target=\"_blank\">About Us</a> page for a complete description.[/accordion_item]\r\n\r\n[accordion_item active=\"no\" title=\"How do I start with Iter Community?\" accordion=\"accordion\"]Before you do anything on the website, please read our <a href=\"http://www.itercom.org/tos\" target=\"_blank\">terms of service</a> and our <a href=\"http://www.itercom.org/privacy/\" target=\"_blank\">privacy policies</a>. If you agree to the policies, then an ideal place to start would be to <a href=\"http://www.itercom.org/blog/\" target=\"_blank\">explore the blog</a> for current information on Iter Community. You could also start on the <a href=\"http://www.itercom.org/past-conferences/\" target=\"_blank\">Past Conferences</a> page to view previous conferences relevant to Iter Community. [/accordion_item]\r\n\r\n[accordion_item active=\"no\" title=\"Does being a member of Iter Community cost anything?\" accordion=\"accordion\"]There is no fee to join the Iter Community website, but registration is required to use most features.[/accordion_item]\r\n\r\n[accordion_item active=\"no\" title=\"Who has access to Iter Community?\" accordion=\"accordion\"]Anyone may view Iter Community. Your access to Iter Community relies on your user role. Please see the <a href=\"http://www.itercom.org/wiki/explanation-iter-community-user-roles/\" target=\"_blank\">Wiki Help Doc on user roles</a> for more information.[/accordion_item]\r\n\r\n[accordion_item active=\"no\" title=\"How do I connect with other members of Iter Community?\" accordion=\"accordion\"]You can connect with other users via the <a href=\"http://www.itercom.org/members/\" target=\"_blank\">members page</a>.[/accordion_item]\r\n\r\n[accordion_item active=\"no\" title=\"Can I invite a colleague to Iter Community?\" accordion=\"accordion\"]You may invite anyone to Iter Community. Access to the website content depends on one\'s user role.[/accordion_item]\r\n\r\n[accordion_item active=\"no\" title=\"Who has access to Iter Community?\" accordion=\"accordion\"]Anyone may access the Iter Community website. However, only specific users with certain user roles can modify the content of Iter Community. Please see the <a href=\"http://www.itercom.org/wiki/explanation-iter-community-user-roles/\" target=\"_blank\">Wiki Help Doc explaining user roles</a>.[/accordion_item]\r\n\r\n[accordion_item active=\"no\" title=\"What are Iter Community user roles?\" accordion=\"accordion\"]User roles establish a ranking system on Iter Community. Site administrators hold the highest ranks, while most users hold the lowest rank. Please see the <a href=\"http://www.itercom.org/wiki/explanation-iter-community-user-roles/\" target=\"_blank\">Wiki Help Doc explaining user roles</a> for more detailed descriptions of each role.[/accordion_item]\r\n\r\n[accordion_item active=\"no\" title=\"How do I post an event in the Events Calendar?\" accordion=\"accordion\"]Please see the <a href=\"http://www.itercom.org/wiki/tutorial-how-to-create-an-event/\" target=\"_blank\">Wiki Help Doc explaining how one can create an event in the calendar</a>.[/accordion_item]\r\n\r\n[accordion_item active=\"no\" title=\"Who should I invite to be in a Group? How will I know if I have been invited into another Group?\" accordion=\"accordion\"]If you are creating a private group, you should only invite the select number of people to be in the group. In a public group, anyone can join without requiring an invitation. If you have been invited to a group, you will receive a WordPress notification.[/accordion_item]\r\n\r\n[accordion_item active=\"no\" title=\"I want to upload previous conference material to the Past Conferences section. How do I do that?\" accordion=\"accordion\"]Create a page with the conference information and set the page to be the child of \"Past Conferences.\" To set pages in a parent/child relationship, navigate to Page Attributes when editing a page, and select the page you wish to be the parent.[/accordion_item]\r\n\r\n[accordion_item active=\"no\" title=\"How can I subscribe to groups on Iter Community?\" accordion=\"accordion\"]Navigate to <a href=\"http://www.itercom.org/groups/\" target=\"_blank\">Groups</a> and join a public group. Private groups require an invitation from the group owner.[/accordion_item]\r\n\r\n[accordion_item active=\"no\" title=\"What are the privacy regulations for Iter Community? Are you going to sell my information to nefarious marketers?\" accordion=\"accordion\"]Iter Community will not sell your information to any unknown third parties. Identifiable personal information will not be disclosed to a third party unless required to by law. Please read the <a href=\"http://www.itercom.org/privacy/\" target=\"_blank\">privacy policies page</a> for more information.[/accordion_item]\r\n\r\n[accordion_item active=\"no\" title=\"How do I send questions, comments, or complaints to the developers of Iter Community?\" accordion=\"accordion\"]You may send a private message to any site administrator. To send a message, navigate to the <a href=\"http://www.itercom.org/members/\" target=\"_blank\">members page</a> and click on an administrator profile, then click private message. Send your message and the administrator will respond as soon as possible.[/accordion_item]\r\n\r\n[accordion_item active=\"no\" title=\"How do I set up a project with Iter Community?\" accordion=\"accordion\"]Navigate to the <a href=\"http://www.itercom.org/project-application-page/\" target=\"_blank\">Projects Application page</a> and fill out the application for project space on Iter Community. Please see the <a href=\"http://www.itercom.org/wiki/explanation-project-applications/\" target=\"_blank\">Wiki Help Doc explaining explaining project applications</a> for more information.[/accordion_item]\r\n\r\n[accordion_item active=\"no\" title=\"Where is my stuff stored? Can I access it at any time?\" accordion=\"accordion\"]We are developing an answer to this question.[/accordion_item]\r\n[/accordion]','FAQs','','publish','closed','closed','','faqs','','','2015-05-22 23:37:40','2015-05-22 23:37:40','',0,'http://chimpgroup.com/wp-demo/aidreform/?page_id=6821',0,'page','',0),(6835,3,'2014-01-08 14:45:02','2014-01-08 14:45:02','<h2>Iter Community</h2>\r\n<b>Iter Community</b> facilitates and supports communication, collaboration, and digital project creation for research communities of the Middle Ages and the Renaissance. It is a social knowledge creation environment, providing a space for users to connect with others in the field, to create and host a digital humanities project, to develop a research community, and to collaborate on intellectual endeavours.\r\n\r\nWhile digital scholarship proliferates, output and interaction often occurs in isolation. Identifying and building a team, launching a digital humanities project, and sustaining a community of practice can be a challenge. Iter Community connects emerging academics, established scholars, alt-ac practitioners, and the public over shared research interests and diverse skill sets. We help scholars build and maintain research communities and provide the necessary infrastructure for digital humanities projects.\r\n\r\nThe features of Iter Community include but are not limited to:\r\n\r\n<strong>Conference resources</strong><ul>\r\n	<li>print and video proceedings</li>\r\n	<li>a calendar of events</li>\r\n	<li>CFPs</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Connection tools</strong><ul>\r\n	<li>discussion groups</li>\r\n	<li>member directory</li>\r\n	<li>member linking and team creation</li>\r\n	<li>social sharing</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Updates</strong><ul>\r\n	<li>field-specific news</li>\r\n	<li>publication announcements</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Other research facilitation resources</strong><ul>\r\n	<li>wiki knowledge database</li>\r\n	<li>access to Iter Bibliography</li>\r\n	<li>personal archive space</li>\r\n	<li>file sharing</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Project hosting</strong><ul>\r\n	<li>critical editions</li>\r\n	<li>knowledgebases</li>\r\n	<li>databases</li>\r\n	<li>e-books</li>\r\n	<li>other digital forms</li>\r\n	<li>on various platforms including CommentPress, Drupal, Git (HTML/CSS), Scalar, and WordPress.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nIter Community is being developed by The Electronic Textual Cultures Lab (University of Victoria) in partnership with Iter (University of Toronto). We are building this environment on top of our own open source infrastructure for digital humanities applications, with the core platform a specialized custom version of Commons-in-a-Box. Iter Community is proudly hosted by the University of Toronto Scarborough.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','About Us','','publish','closed','closed','','about-us','','','2015-05-20 20:05:06','2015-05-20 20:05:06','',0,'http://chimpgroup.com/wp-demo/aidreform/?page_id=6835',0,'page','',0),(6998,3,'2014-01-31 10:03:06','2014-01-31 10:03:06','<h5>University we offer a broad range of learning environments which incl ude the traditional lecture-tutorial interactive workshops labo ratory and practical activities, student-led seminars.</h5>\nSuavely less belligerent by stuck much wow effective newt less far far became alongside 